Un objectif fisheye, c'est peut-être un peu trop pour un nichoir.
On apprend de ses erreurs.
J'aurais dû le savoir, vu que j'en a déjà fabriqué un avec un objectif "normal".
Je vous en dirai plus ce week-end quand j'aurai installé le deuxième que j'ai fabriqué.
Disons que les oiseaux auront une meilleure connexion Internet que la mienne en 2015.
Or at least, that's the goal.
The box that already contains a birdhouse is using the house's Wi-Fi.
There's still work to do to connect the other one.
Well, I hung the other birdhouse during the day. Here's how it looks in a good spot in the garden.
But, little flashback: "What's inside?", don't I hear ask.
At the top is one of these ESP32 modules with a fisheye lens camera and an infrared LED that I scavenged from a Raspberry Pi device.
Because this plastic box has an odd shape, it's due to the pivoting side panel of the birdhouse. I bought it as is and couldn't modify it, so I had to design my setup around it.
Since there's no electricity in the garden, the entire system is powered by a solar panel and a 18650 cell with a capacity of 2600 mAh.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here's a picture of the panel.
The gray box hanging on the side of the birdhouse houses the battery.
At full charge, it gives me about 4 hours of power.
I call that a feature. So the birds can have a bit of privacy too.
Initially, I wasn't sure if the internet connection in our garden would be good enough for this installation. The old access points that I replaced last fall wouldn't have been sufficient.
But the new ones cover the area well.
It's almost disappointing because I had planned to mount a TP-Link CPE210 on the roof and aim it downwards towards the garden.
I could always do it when I install more camera birdhouses, especially in areas far from the house, I might need them.
Now, for reasons I can't quite explain right now, the camera is offline. It turned off barely an hour after sunset.
The battery charge might have stopped three hours before sunset due to lack of light.
Maybe it couldn't fully charge in just under half a day.
I'll see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have a battery telemetry system. I might add one in a future revision.
A few more sensors would be nice, I think.
And maybe a battery that can hold a full night, at least on paper.
Oh, and another lens.
The fisheye is much too wide.
But I'm already looking at parts on Digikey, so I might just make a custom PCB for this use.
Or not. We'll see.
And, it's still offline.
Great.
Given the solar panels installed on the house, the sun is really high for only about 90 minutes.
Wait another hour or two to see what happens or doesn't happen.
Still offline.
Nothing is ever simple.
In fact, on the USB-C board I was using to plug in the battery charger, the 5V and ground were reversed.
I swapped the wires, and now I have a charging indicator.
The ESP did not connect right away, let's wait a few minutes.
An hour later: still offline.
It seems it keeps restarting in a loop and triggers the Tasmota reset function.
I think the panel is just crap. I ordered a bigger one, hoping it will work.
Look what I found in the workshop.
A 24V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is so low (and partly hidden behind a tree) that it drops almost to nothing as soon as I start using it.
I think I'll wait until tomorrow to see if it's enough for this installation or if I need the best panel I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought the panel in 2021, and it should generate 12V at a maximum of 1.2A.
So either something is wrong with this panel or with my multimeter, or they've changed the specifications.
Good news, everyone!
The specifications have changed and mine is defective.
The titles of the old and new specifications mention a 12V, 10W panel.
This is why I don't delete my old emails.
Hey, look: the thing reconnected for about a minute about an hour ago.
Maybe the panel charged the battery just enough for 38 seconds of power. That would have taken a bit over two hours.
Guess what: it's cloudy today. So I'm not sure that broken solar panel is capable of generating enough energy to do anything.
Let's see.
Latest update: I installed the new panel and it seems to be working.
It might all turn off at sunset, but let's see.
By the way, I'm using ping integration in Home Assistant to monitor if it's connected or not.
The round-trip time is 102 ms. Not great, but not bad.
